Here’s a **clear, practical explanation** of the difference between  
**`obj.key`** and **`obj[key]`** in JavaScript 👇

***

## ✅ Short Answer

| Syntax     | When to use                                                  |
| ---------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ |
| `obj.key`  | When the **property name is fixed and known**                |
| `obj[key]` | When the **property name is dynamic (stored in a variable)** |

***

## 1️⃣ `obj.key` → **Dot notation**

### ✅ Use when the property name is **literal**

```js
const obj = {
  name: "JS",
  version: "ES6"
};

console.log(obj.name);    // "JS"
console.log(obj.version); // "ES6"
```

### 🔒 Rules

*   Property name must be:
    *   a **valid identifier**
    *   known at **write time**
*   ❌ Cannot use variables

```js
const key = "name";
console.log(obj.key); // ❌ undefined (looks for literal "key")
```

***

## 2️⃣ `obj[key]` → **Bracket notation**

### ✅ Use when the property name is **dynamic**

```js
const obj = {
  name: "JS",
  version: "ES6"
};

const key = "name";
console.log(obj[key]); // ✅ "JS"
```

### ✅ Also required when:

*   Property name has **spaces**
*   Property name starts with a **number**
*   Property name has **special characters**

```js
const user = {
  "first name": "Shekar",
  "1role": "Admin"
};

console.log(user["first name"]); // ✅ "Shekar"
console.log(user["1role"]);      // ✅ "Admin"
```

❌ Dot notation fails here:

```js
user.first name // ❌ syntax error
user.1role     // ❌ invalid
```

***

## 🔑 Key Difference (Interview Important)

### Dot notation

```js
obj.key
```

➡️ Always looks for property named **"key"**

### Bracket notation

```js
obj[key]
```

➡️ Looks for property whose name is the **value of `key`**

***

## 3️⃣ Real Example (Why your earlier code returned `undefined`)

```js
const obj = {
  name: "JS"
};

const key = "shekar";

console.log(obj[key]); // undefined
```

Because JavaScript evaluates:

```js
obj["shekar"] // property does not exist
```

***

## 4️⃣ When both give same result

```js
obj.name      === obj["name"]; // ✅ true
```

Only when:

*   Property name is valid
*   Property name is known
*   No variables involved

***

## 5️⃣ Real‑World Use Cases

### ✅ Use `obj.key`

*   Simple objects
*   Config files
*   Known properties

```js
config.apiUrl
user.isActive
```

### ✅ Use `obj[key]`

*   Loops
*   API responses
*   Dynamic data
*   Forms

```js
for (let key in obj) {
  console.log(obj[key]);
}
```

***

## ✅ Final Summary (One‑Glance)

| Feature            | `obj.key` | `obj[key]` |
| ------------------ | --------- | ---------- |
| Uses variable      | ❌         | ✅          |
| Dynamic access     | ❌         | ✅          |
| Special characters | ❌         | ✅          |
| Simple & readable  | ✅         | ❌          |
| Interview safe     | ✅         | ✅          |

***

### 🧠 One line to remember

> **Use dot notation for static access, bracket notation for dynamic access.**

